<subSubSection id="51DA6520FF98FFF9A3E3BF50FE07F726" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3E3BF50FBCBF67F" blockId="6.[136,1054,1026,1088]" box="[136,1054,1066,1088]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3E3BF50FF6FF600" bold="true" box="[136,186,1066,1087]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<typeStatus id="C67B8809FF98FFF9A3E3BF50FF6FF600" box="[136,186,1066,1087]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Type</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A238BF50FDE6F67F" author="Britton, N. L. &amp; Rose, J. N." box="[339,563,1066,1088]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" refId="ref7915" refString="Britton, N. L. &amp; Rose, J. N. (1920) The Cactaceae. Descriptions and Illustrations of Plants of the Cactus Family vols. 1 - 2. The Carnegie Institution, Washington, 241 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 46288" type="book" year="1920">Britton &amp; Rose 1920: 3</bibRefCitation>
):— 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A130BF50FC98F67F" authority="Miller" authorityName="Miller" box="[603,845,1066,1088]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hexagonus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A130BF50FCDEF600" box="[603,779,1066,1087]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Cereus hexagonus</emphasis>
Miller
</taxonomicName>
(1768: 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A0FCBF50FC0FF600" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1754" box="[919,986,1066,1087]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A0FCBF50FC0FF600" box="[919,986,1066,1087]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Cereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
no. 1).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3E3BF14FC96F692" blockId="6.[136,1452,1134,1520]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3E3BF14FEB8F6B7" bold="true" box="[136,365,1134,1160]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Species richness:—</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="A9A83CF6FF98FFF9A206BF14FCEBF692" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3746878302" collectorName="Taylor &amp; Zappi" location="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Rio Grande do Sul">
The genus comprises circa 20 species (
<collectorName id="B435537DFF98FFF9A074BF14FCBFF6B7" box="[799,874,1134,1160]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Taylor</collectorName>
&amp; 
<collectorName id="B435537DFF98FFF9A0E7BF14FC07F6B7" box="[908,978,1134,1160]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Zappi</collectorName>
: 269), of whick one are represented in 
<collectingRegion id="DB04F849FF98FFF9A6E8BF14FEF9F693" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A253BFE9FCEBF692" authority="Schumann (1890: 202)" authorityName="K. Schumann" authorityPageNumber="202" authorityYear="1890" box="[312,830,1170,1197]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hildmannianus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A253BFE9FDE6F693" box="[312,563,1170,1197]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Cereus hildmannianus</emphasis>
Schumann (1890: 202)
</taxonomicName>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BFCCFE07F726" blockId="6.[136,1452,1134,1520]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BFCCFE02F6EF" bold="true" box="[189,471,1206,1232]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">General distribution:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A2BCBFCDFDF0F6EE" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1754" box="[471,549,1207,1233]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A2BCBFCDFDF0F6EE" box="[471,549,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Cereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is naturally distribuited in South America, ocurring in northern 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A78FBFCCFA83F6EF" box="[1252,1366,1206,1232]" name="Argentina" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A60BBFCCFA72F6EF" box="[1376,1447,1206,1232]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A3E3BFA0FF08F6CB" box="[136,221,1242,1268]" name="Bolivia" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A383BFA0FE8CF6CB" box="[232,345,1242,1268]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, French Guiana, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A173BFA0FCD5F6CB" box="[536,768,1242,1268]" name="Curaçao" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Netherlands Antilles</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A067BFA1FCA0F6CA" box="[780,885,1243,1269]" name="Paraguay" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A0EBBFA1FC63F6CA" box="[896,950,1243,1269]" name="Peru" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A0AABFA1FBCEF6CA" box="[961,1051,1243,1269]" name="Guyana" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A74DBFA0FB41F6CB" box="[1062,1172,1242,1268]" name="Suriname" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Suriname</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A7F4BFA0FAA2F6CB" box="[1183,1399,1242,1269]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Trinidad &amp; Tobago</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A3E3BF84FF2EF727" box="[136,251,1278,1304]" name="Venezuela" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A261BF85FE13F726" author="Hunt, D. R. &amp; Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G." box="[266,454,1278,1305]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" refId="ref8565" refString="Hunt, D. R., Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G. (Eds.) (2006) The New Cactus Lexicon. Dh Books, Milborne Port, 373 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Hunt 
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A221BF85FE56F727" box="[330,387,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="51DA6520FF98FFF9A3D6BE58FF2FF7CF" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BE58FB4DF7BB" blockId="6.[136,1452,1134,1520]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BE58FD15F703" bold="true" box="[189,704,1314,1340]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
In SMRB, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A055BE59FBEFF703" authorityName="K. Schumann" authorityYear="1890" box="[830,1082,1314,1341]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hildmannianus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A055BE59FBEFF703" box="[830,1082,1314,1341]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Cereus hildmannianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also present where (
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF98FFF9A628BE58FA4BF702" box="[1347,1438,1314,1341]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,609,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-168@7.[302,1286,605,1916]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Cereus hildmaninanus (whitish-pink flowers). B) Echinopsis oxygona (pink flowers). C) Frailea albifusca. D) Frailea castanea. E) Frailea albifusca.F) Frailea lepida.G) Frailea mammifera. H) Frailea pumila. I) Frailea pygmaea.J) Frailea erythracantha K) Gymnocalycium denudatum (white flowers). L) Gymnocalycium uruguayense (yellow flowers). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415611/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), it widely distributed in the study area (
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF98FFF9A151BE3CFDA9F75E" box="[570,636,1350,1377]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1201,1223]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1174]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,187,1174]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Location of the Santa Maria River Basin. Pictures by R. Trentin" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415609/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), as well as throughout 
<collectingRegion id="DB04F849FF98FFF9A0E7BE3CFB88F75F" box="[908,1117,1350,1376]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A706BE3CFA86F75E" author="Carneiro, A. M. &amp; Farias-Singer, R. &amp; Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D." box="[1133,1363,1350,1377]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" refId="ref8113" refString="Carneiro, A. M., Farias-Singer, R., Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D. (2016) Cactos do Rio Grande do Sul. Fundacao Zoobotanica do Rio Grande do Sul, Porto Alegre, 224 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Carneiro 
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A7B3BE3DFADCF75F" box="[1240,1289,1350,1376]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
), which may occur in native grasslands, rocky outcrops and forests, sometimes behaving as epiphyte.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BEF4FF2FF7CF" blockId="6.[136,1452,1134,1520]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BEF4FE13F796" bold="true" box="[189,454,1422,1449]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
This species characterized in having a shrubby habit (up to 8 meters high), columnar cylindrical branches, 8–12 ribbed with white-pink flowers, blooms from October to January, fruitin time shortly thereafter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
